### History

Back in the latter half of the 20th century, the [Philadelphia Convention Hall and Civic Center](/Philadelphia_Convention_Hall_and_Civic_Center) was, shall we say, *past its prime*. With the advent of the [Spectrum](/Spectrum_(arena)) in [South Philadelphia](/South_Philadelphia), it lost its luster for major sporting and entertainment spectacles. Even political conventions outgrew its rather modest capacity. By the 1980s, the powers that be, both regional and state, began hatching plans for a new convention center. A shiny, modern edifice, situated right in the throbbing heart of [Center City](/Center_City,_Philadelphia).

The chosen location? The old train shed of the [Reading Terminal](/Reading_Terminal). A bit of historical irony, perhaps, repurposing a hub of transit for… gatherings. After a period of renovations, meticulously overseen by the firm of [Wilson Brothers & Company](/Wilson_Brothers_%26_Company), it finally opened its doors in 1993. And with its grand unveiling, most of the events that had languished at the Civic Center, including the esteemed [Philadelphia Flower Show](/Philadelphia_Flower_Show), were unceremoniously relocated.

The construction, however, came at a cost. Buildings in [Chinatown](/Chinatown,_Philadelphia), specifically those along [Arch Street](/Arch_Street_(Philadelphia)) up to the intersection with 13th Street, were unceremoniously demolished. A brutal efficiency, if nothing else. [1]

